OK, so I am investigating a fix. It comes in two parts: first is modifying [these lines](https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/master/conda/resolve.py#L340-L348) in resolve.py so that `prune_features` isn't called first, but second. If you're daring, here's the replacement:
```
        # Iterate in the filtering process until no more progress is made
        if filtered:
            pruned = True
            while pruned:
                for s in list(specs):
                    pruned = False
                    if not s.optional:
                        pruned += filter_group([s], None)
                        if unsat and sat_only:
                            return False
                    pruned += prune_features()
```
That causes the solver to pick up numpy and spasms properly, but it _doesn't_ pick up scipy. The reason for this, I think, is that there is no `scipy 0.17.0` available with the `openblas` feature, so it prefers to install the one without it than the older version with it.

Whether _that_ is a bug is probably up for discussion. My thinking is that yes, it is: if a feature is present in the environment, any package that has that among its options should use it, even if that means selecting an older version. @kalefranz, @groutr, what do you think? If we agree on this point, then I know how to fix it---it requires an additional `optimize()` call to maximize the total number of packages installed with `features` active.

